These fourteen (14) individual elements of this prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases and minimize impacts if an incident were to occur. Marathon and its employees are committed to the standards required by these management programs. In addition to the above elements, MPLX also has specific prevention measures that are employed as part of the Terminal's operating procedures and engineering and administrative controls to help identify/contain/control a release, and reduce the consequences of a release. These are briefly summarized as follows:

General Risk Reduction and Safety Measures

-Engineering and construction in accordance with recognized industry and company standards;
-Equipment properly designed with protection from overpressure (pressure safety relief valves, etc.);
-Updated technical drawings, Piping & Instrument Diagrams and Process/Block Flow Diagrams;
-Operating systems monitored and controlled by trained Operators;
-Redundant control systems;
-Manual shutdown devices for critical systems;
-Scheduled inspection and testing of safety devices;
-Limited/secured facility access;
-Regular safety meetings and safety awareness programs;
-Routinely scheduled safety inspections and audits; and
-Frequent unit surveillance by operators.

General Release Mitigation

-Process and remotely operated shutoffs to limit release quantity (also actuated via a fusible
element);
-Excess Flow Valves;
-Hydrocarbon Detectors with automatic process shutdown function; 
-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks; and
-Smart-Hose
